Praet: It is far more difficult to combat deflation when in the midst of it. We would have to spend much more and outcome more uncertain.
Praet: We have to use all instruments of monetary policy to ensure price stability across the euro area.
Praet: With inflation target of 0%, there would be no buffer. If an economic shock occurs in such cases, you have deflation straight away.
Praet: For good reasons, ECB defined price stability as inflation close to, but below, 2% over medium term – with support of the Bundesbank.
Praet: If inflation would rise to 4%, all would expect ECB to do something about it. So, ECB also has to step in when inflation falls to 0

ECB announces expanded asset purchase programme http://t.co/ZjqilJ9cAA
ECB announces a modification to the interest rate applicable to future targeted longer-term refinancing operations http://t.co/kMHS99IEtz
Introductory statement Mario Draghi to the press conference http://t.co/oo5nceJ2V0
Draghi: Bubbles of a local nature should be addressed by local instruments, not by monetary policy
Draghi: After redemption of Greek bonds in July purchases could take place if conditions fulfilled
Draghi: We don't have a special rule for Greece but there are some conditions that need to be fulfilled
Draghi: Maturities of purchased securities range between two and thirty years
Draghi: There was consensus on risk-sharing of 20/80%
Draghi: A large majority was in favour of taking measures now
Draghi: GovC was unanimous in stating that asset purchase programme is a true monetary policy tool in a legal sense
Draghi: MonPol can create basis for growth but it's up to governments and Commission to make sure growth actually takes place
Draghi: Singleness of monetary policy remains in place
Draghi: Principle of risk sharing kept in place but we wanted to mitigate concerns about potential unintended fiscal consequences
Draghi: Has nothing to do with singleness of monetary policy because decisions are taken by GovC
Draghi: Dutch and Luxembourg central bank indemnified for losses in the past
Draghi: GovC has used discretion to deviate from full risk-sharing more often in the past
Draghi: Every monetary policy action always has some fiscal implication
Draghi: Not more than 30% of issuer and 25% of issue to be purchased
Draghi: We'll buy up to a percentage that will allow proper price formation
Draghi: Today's measures will decisively underpin the firm anchoring of medium to long term inflation expectations
Draghi: This implies that 20% of the additional asset purchases will be subject to a regime of risk sharing
Draghi: The ECB will hold 8% of the additional asset purchases
Draghi: The rest of the NCBs’ additional asset purchases will not be subject to loss sharing
Draghi: GovC decided that purchases of securities of European institutions (12% of additional purchases) will be subject to loss sharing
Draghi: GovC retains control over all features of programme and ECB to coordinate the purchases to safeguard singleness of monetary policy
Draghi: Interest rate of future TLTRO operations will be equal to MRO rate prevailing at the time when each TLTRO is conducted
Draghi: Governing Council decided to change the pricing of the six remaining targeted longer-term refinancing operations (TLTROs)
Draghi: Additional eligibility criteria to be applied in the case of countries under an EU/IMF adjustment programme
Draghi: Purchases start in March 2015 and include investment-grade euro area govt, agency and EU institution securities in sec market
Draghi: Purchases until sustained adjustment in inflation path consistent with aim of inflation close to, but below 2% over the medium term
Draghi: Combined monthly purchases will be €60 billion, to be carried out at least until end-Sept 2016
Draghi: Launch of expanded asset purchase programme, which includes existing purchase programmes for asset-backed securities & covered bonds
